# Webhook Endpoints (High Limits - 200/minute)
###############################################################################

### Test 32: Circle Webhook (200/minute by IP)
POST {{baseUrl}}/webhooks/circle
Content-Type: application/json
X-Circle-Signature: test_signature

{
  "eventType": "transaction.completed",
  "transactionId": "txn_123456"
}

### Test 33: Twilio Webhook (200/minute by IP)
POST {{baseUrl}}/webhooks/twilio
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

MessageSid=SM123456&From=+2250700000000&Body=Test

###############################################################################
# Notes
###############################################################################

# Rate Limit Testing Tips:
#
# 1. Use a loop to send multiple requests quickly:
#    - In VS Code: Click "Send Request" multiple times
#    - Or use bash: for i in {1..10}; do curl ...; done
#
# 2. Watch for rate limit headers in responses:
#    - X-RateLimit-Limit: Maximum allowed
#    - X-RateLimit-Remaining: Requests left
#    - X-RateLimit-Reset: Unix timestamp when limit resets
#
# 3. When rate limited (429):
#    - Wait for Retry-After seconds
#    - Or wait until X-RateLimit-Reset timestamp
#
# 4. Rate limits are per:
#    - IP address (for auth endpoints)
#    - User ID (for authenticated endpoints)
#
# 5. Test with different users/IPs:
#    - Same IP, different users: Separate rate limits
#    - Same user, different IPs: Shared rate limit
#
# 6. Redis-backed limits:
#    - Limits are shared across server instances
#    - Survives server restarts
#    - Check Redis: redis-cli GET "rate_limit:user:123:endpoint"
